\description{
Estimates the Bayesian progressive three-state model for interval-censored
three-state screening outcomes with censoring after intervention
(Klausch et al., 2023). The model is fitted using a Gibbs sampler with data
augmentation for the latent event times \code{X} and \code{S}, and either slice-sampling
or Metropolis-Hastings updates for the transition-model parameters.
}
\details{
The function fits a Bayesian accelerated failure-time model for progressive
three-state screening outcomes with censoring after intervention. The time
from state 1 to state 2 is denoted \code{X}, and the time from state 2 to state 3
is denoted \code{S}. In each Gibbs iteration, the latent transition times are
updated by data augmentation conditional on the current parameter values, and
the transition-model parameters are updated using either slice-sampling or
random-walk Metropolis-Hastings steps.

The observed data are supplied through the event indicator \code{d} and interval
bounds \code{L} and \code{R}, with optional covariate matrices \code{Z.X} and \code{Z.S}. The
distributions of the latent times \code{X} and \code{S} are specified by \code{dist.X} and
\code{dist.S}.

By default, \code{L} and \code{R} are divided by the median of the finite right interval
bounds before sampling. The fitted object stores the observed data on the
original time scale. Klausch et al. (2023) did not rescale time. However, in
an AFT model the intercept is measured on the log-time scale, so a fixed
default prior on the intercept can have different shrinkage behavior under
arbitrary choices of the time unit. Rescaling by a typical observed time scale
makes the default prior less sensitive to the units in which time is supplied.
This behavior can be disabled with \code{rescale_times = FALSE}.

The default prior is evaluated by \code{\link[=log_aft_prior]{log_aft_prior()}}. For each transition model,
the AFT parameter vector contains the intercept first, followed by the slope
coefficients, with \code{log(sigma)} in the final position. With
\code{log_prior_fun = log_aft_prior} and \code{beta.prior = "t"}, independent
Student-\eqn{t} priors are assigned to the regression coefficients. The
degrees of freedom are given by \code{beta.prior.X} for the \code{X} model and
\code{beta.prior.S} for the \code{S} model. With \code{beta.prior = "norm"}, independent
normal priors are assigned to the regression coefficients, and
\code{beta.prior.X} and \code{beta.prior.S} are interpreted as prior standard
deviations.

The scale parameters \code{sigma_X} and \code{sigma_S} can either be estimated or fixed.
When \code{fix.sigma.X = FALSE} and \code{fix.sigma.S = FALSE}, the respective scale
parameters are estimated. Under the default prior function, normal prior
kernels restricted to positive values are used for \code{sigma_X} and \code{sigma_S},
with prior standard deviations \code{sig.prior.X} and \code{sig.prior.S}, respectively.
Equivalently, these are half-normal priors up to an additive constant in the
log-prior. The Jacobian adjustment for the \code{log(sigma)} parameterization is
included by the prior function. When \code{fix.sigma.X = TRUE} or
\code{fix.sigma.S = TRUE}, the corresponding scale parameter is fixed throughout
sampling, with \code{sig.prior.X} and/or \code{sig.prior.S} giving the fixed value. For
example, \code{fix.sigma.S = TRUE} with \code{sig.prior.S = 1} fixes \code{sigma_S} at 1
during estimation. If, in addition, \code{dist.S = "weibull"} is chosen, the
latent \code{S} transition follows the exponential special case of the Weibull
model.

Custom prior functions can be supplied through \code{log_prior_fun}. The same prior
function is currently used for the \code{X} and \code{S} transition models, but the
prior parameters may differ between the two models. Specifically,
\code{beta.prior.X} and \code{sig.prior.X} are passed as \code{tau} and \code{sig.prior} to the
prior function for the \code{X} model, while \code{beta.prior.S} and \code{sig.prior.S} are
passed as \code{tau} and \code{sig.prior} to the prior function for the \code{S} model.
Additional prior parameters, if needed, should currently be hardcoded inside
the custom prior function. See \code{\link[=log_aft_prior]{log_aft_prior()}} for details on the required
parameter vector and on how to modify the default prior.

Klausch et al. (2023) used random-walk Metropolis-Hastings updates for the
transition-model parameters. This can be requested with \code{MH = TRUE}. The
current default is \code{MH = FALSE}, which uses a slice sampler instead. In
practice, the slice sampler has shown faster convergence. The default
step-out size \code{slicesampler_stepsize = 1} usually works well, but it can be
increased or decreased if the slice sampler needs further tuning.

Passing a previous fitted object through \code{prev.run} continues an earlier MCMC
run rather than starting from scratch. In that case, the function initializes
from the last sampled parameter values of the previous run and reuses the
stored data, covariates, priors, proposal settings, distributions, fixed-scale
settings, prior function, sampler choice, and controller settings.

If \code{update_till_convergence = TRUE}, the function checks convergence after
the initial run and repeatedly extends the sampler by \code{mc_update} iterations
per chain until the convergence criteria based on \code{min_R} and \code{min_eff} are
satisfied, or until \code{maxit} is reached. Progress is printed after each
extension run of \code{mc_update} iterations per chain.
}
\examples{
library(BayesTSM)

# Generate data
dat = gendat(
              n = 1000,  # Sample size
              p = 2,     # Number of normal distributed covariates
              r = 0,     # Correlation of the covariates
              sigma.X = 0.3,         # True scale parameter
              mu.X    = 2,           # True intercept parameter
              beta.X  = c(0.5,0.5),  # True slope parameters
              sigma.S = 0.5,         # True scale parameter
              mu.S    = 1,           # True intercept parameters
              beta.S  = c(0.5,0.5),  # True slope parameters
              dist.X  = 'weibull',   # Distribution of X
              dist.S  = 'weibull',   # Distribution of S
              v.min   = 1,           # Min time between screening moments
              v.max   = 5,           # Max time between screening moments
              Tmax    = 2e2,         # Max number of screening times
              mean.rc = 10           # Mean time to right censoring
            )

# Run bayestsm Gibbs sampler with data augmentation and slice sampling of the parameters
mod_slice   = bayestsm(
             d              = dat$d,
             L              = dat$L,
             R              = dat$R,
             Z.X            = dat[,c('Z.1','Z.2')],
             Z.S            = dat[,c('Z.1','Z.2')],
             mc             = 1e4,
             warmup         = 5e2,              # discarded before assessing convergence
             thinning        = 10,               # The chain can be thinned to save memory
             chains         = 2,                # In practice use more than 2 chains
             update_till_convergence = FALSE,
             MH             = FALSE,            # set to TRUE for Metropolis sampling
             dist.X         = 'weibull',        # Correctly specified distributions
             dist.S         = 'weibull'
             )

# Run bayestsm Gibbs sampler with data augmentation and Metropolis sampling of the parameters
mod_MH      = bayestsm(
             d              = dat$d,
             L              = dat$L,
             R              = dat$R,
             Z.X            = dat[,c('Z.1','Z.2')],
             Z.S            = dat[,c('Z.1','Z.2')],
             mc             = 1e4,
             warmup         = 5e2,              # discarded before assessing convergence
             thinning        = 10,               # The chain can be thinned to save memory
             chains         = 2,                # In practice use more than 2 chains
             update_till_convergence = FALSE,
             MH             = TRUE,             # set to TRUE for Metropolis sampling
             dist.X         = 'weibull',        # Correctly specified distributions
             dist.S         = 'weibull'
             )

}
\references{
Klausch, T., Akwiwu, E. M. U., van de Wiel, M. A., Coupé, V. M. H., and
Berkhof, J. (2023). A Bayesian accelerated failure time model for interval
censored three-state screening outcomes. \emph{The Annals of Applied
Statistics}, 17(2), 1285--1306. \doi{10.1214/22-AOAS1669}
}
